in units of the Planck's constant.

275
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:30,000
The e arises because the...

276
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:35,000
because to go a little step involves the...

277
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:37,000
something very...

278
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:38,000
You have to multiply these.

279
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:39,000
Yes.

280
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:40,000
Both together.

281
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:41,000
Right. Exactly.

282
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:43,000
That's exactly right.

283
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:45,000
And the other thing here is the i.

284
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:47,000
The i is part of quantum mechanics.

285
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,000
What can I say?

286
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:49,000
Yeah.

287
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:51,000
That sum is the probability?

288
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:54,000
That sum is the thing whose square is the probability.

289
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:57,000
By square, I mean times its complex conjugate.

290
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
This sum could hardly be a probability

291
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
because in general it's complex.

292
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,000
It's got an i in it.

293
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:04,000
If you multiply it,

294
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:06,000
you get the sum of all possible roots.

295
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:09,000
If you multiply it by its complex conjugate,

296
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:10,000
that is the probability.

297
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,000
This is the probability amplitude.

298
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,000
The complex thing...

299
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:17,000
So this is Feynman's formulation of quantum mechanics.

300
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:21,000
And now it can be extended to quantum field theory.

301
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:24,000
In quantum field theory, the corresponding question...

302
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:25,500
Now we're not actually going

303
00:14:25,500 --> 00:14:27,000
to formulate it this way because...

304
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
But this is a correct way to formulate it.

305
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
We're going to fudge it a little bit

306
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,000
and make our way through it without any rigor.

307
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:36,000
But the same idea.

308
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,000
You start with an arbitrary configuration of the field.

309
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:41,000
All right?

310
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:45,000
So that's some initial phi of x.

311
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,000
x now being just x and not t.

312
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:51,000
An initial configuration of the field.

313
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,500
And now you look at

314
00:14:52,500 --> 00:14:54,000
some final configuration of the field.

315
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:57,000
Let's call it phi prime of x.

316
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,000
These are two different functions.

317
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:00,500
And you can see that the first

318
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:02,000
one is a function of the field.

319
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,000
And the second one is a function of the field.

320
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:08,000
And you can ask, what is the probability amplitude

321
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:10,000
that if I start the field at some value

322
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:12,000
and let the system go

323
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:15,000
and then detect the field at a later time...

324
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:21,000
Imagine you had some way of starting an initial condition

325
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:24,000
with a field being prescribed at every point of space.

326
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Of course, that's an idealization.

327
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:27,500
You don't have a chance in

328
00:15:27,500 --> 00:15:29,000
the world of doing that, really.

329
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:33,000
But you had some sort of apparatus

330
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:36,000
which allowed you to start

331
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:39,000
the field in an arbitrary configuration,

332
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
let it go,

333
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:43,000
and then you had another apparatus

334
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:46,000
which detects the values of the field at every point.

335
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:49,000
Then you can ask, what is the probability

336
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:51,000
that if you start the field in a given way

337
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:53,000
that at a later time

338
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:55,000
the field will have some value?

339
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Again, that probability is determined

340
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:01,000
in terms of a probability amplitude.

341
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,000
And the probability amplitude

342
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:07,000
is...

343
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:10,000
Again, the sum over

344
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:14,000
all possible ways of interpolating

345
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:17,000
the field between initial and final,

346
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:20,000
all possible...

347
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
Exactly what I said.

348
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
All possible ways of filling in

349
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:27,000
between the initial state and the final state

350
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:31,000
with a field value at every point

351
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,000
of e to the minus i a,

352
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:35,000
and then you have the field action.

353
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
That's the integral d x, d

354
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,000
t, d x, d y, d z,

355
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:41,000
d 4 x,

356
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,000
of the Lagrangian,

357
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:47,000
which is a function of phi

358
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:50,000
and the derivatives of phi.

359
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:53,000
So you evaluate the Lagrangian at every point,

360
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:55,000
integrate it up.

361
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:58,000
That gives you the action for a particular...

362
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:00,000
Let's call it a trajectory.

363
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,000
It's not really a trajectory in any ordinary sense.

364
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:04,000
But it's a history.

365
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,000
Let's call it a history, better yet.

366
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,000
For each history,

367
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:10,000
each possible history that you can imagine,

368
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:12,000
it doesn't have to be a true history,

369
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:13,000
a real history,

370
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:15,000
for every possible history you can imagine,

371
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:17,000
there is an action.

372
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:19,000
The action is itself an integral.

373
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:23,000
But then you can sum this over all possible histories,

374
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:25,000
and that is the amplitude

375
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:28,000
to start with a field value phi

376
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:31,000
and end with a field value phi prime

377
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:33,000
between these two trajectories here.

378
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Okay?

379
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:38,000
That's the notion of a path integral.

380
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:39,000
Yeah?

381
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:44,000
I'm not concerned that they're infinite number paths,

