01:00:56,054 --> 01:00:57,554
and we want to know what

1308
01:00:57,554 --> 01:00:59,054
the probability for the two particles

1309
01:00:59,054 --> 01:01:00,054
to go to two other particles.

1310
01:01:00,054 --> 01:01:03,054
In other words, we want to start,

1311
01:01:03,054 --> 01:01:05,554
and I'm going to take the case where

1312
01:01:05,554 --> 01:01:08,054
there are only two layers for a moment.

1313
01:01:08,054 --> 01:01:11,054
There's the case with only two layers for a moment.

1314
01:01:11,054 --> 01:01:14,054
And I want to know the probability

1315
01:01:14,054 --> 01:01:17,054
that if I start a particle over here,

1316
01:01:17,054 --> 01:01:19,054
it will get to here.

1317
01:01:19,054 --> 01:01:20,554
No, if I start two particles,

1318
01:01:20,554 --> 01:01:22,054
one over here and one over here,

1319
01:01:22,054 --> 01:01:24,054
that they'll get to here.

1320
01:01:24,054 --> 01:01:26,054
Okay.

1321
01:01:26,054 --> 01:01:28,054
Well, come back to this term.

1322
01:01:28,054 --> 01:01:29,054
Now remember what this term did for me before.

1323
01:01:29,054 --> 01:01:35,054
Before, it allowed me to hop three units.

